title: For Sale:  L.C. Smith 10 Gauge; "Project Gun"
postcontent: This is a 10 gauge LC Smith SxS hammerless shotgun in Field grade.  It has 32 inch damascuss twist steel barrels choked modified and full. There is a brass bead sight on the barrel and a small hole just behind it where the original white bead was.  These replacement beads are available.  The interior of the barrels are shiney with a few imperfections.  There is no visible rust on this gun.  The lock plates are silver, no case color is showing.  The lock plates have border line engraving around them and LC Smith is engraved on each.  The opening lever has light engraving on it as does the barrel bosses and the underside of the water table.  Serial number is 22791which appears on the forend and barrels also which places it before 1913.  The splinter forend has an ivory insert in a v configeration and it has a fine crack which was reparied previously and the checkering is worn.  The stock has a broken butt plate which is of a dog watching a falling duck or goose. A replacement butt plate is available.  There is a small chip missing from the heel of the stock and another chip missing from the toe.  There is a finger of walnut missing from the stock on the right side next to the trigger guard that would need to be replaced. The figuering and grain of the walnut is very nice but the checkering is worn down.  Tha action operates and locks up tight.  The safety is a 3 position one I believe.  Action needs cleaning and lubricating.This gun is in NRA Antique Firearm Condition Standard; GOOD as a collector firearm.  In perfect shape it would be worth $1,800 + or -  The Old 10 gauge Girl would be a great addition to any Elsie collection as they didn't make all that many 10 gauge guns; only 1,795 between 1886 and 1913.Get yourself a winter time project and have a piece of classic American Shotgun History.

title: For Sale:  WWI, German Gewehr 98 Amberg 8mm Mauser
location: Santa Fe, Santa Fe, New Mexico
postcontent: All parts are matching, including the cleaning rod and stock. The mechanics are excellent and the bore is very fine. The stock is fine. This rifle has the initials "EWB" (EinwohnerWehrBayarn) burned into the right side of the butt, indicating service with the Freikorps just after the war. The Freikorps were mercenary units in Germany, made up of returning veterans, who fought to put down Communist uprisings. They were officially disbanded in 1920, deemed a violation of the Treaty of Versailles. Original, WWI, German Gewehr 98 manufactured at Amberg Arsenal in 1917. Chambered for the 7.92x57mm cartridge (8mm Mauser), The Gew. 98 was the standard German Infantry Weapon of the First World War. This rifle is in very fine condition with about 95% of its factory blued finish remaining and an arsenal bright bolt. No pitting. It is well marked with acceptance stamps.

title: For Sale:  Colt 10th cavalry identified 1860 1st model Richards conversion. (C13238)
postcontent: Colt 10th cavalry identified 1860 1st model Richards conversion. Colt 1860 1st model Richards Conversion inscribed to Captain Nicholas Nolan 10th Cavalry. Very historical gun! This gun belonged to a Civil War Cavalry Officer, then a Captain in the legendary 10th Cavalry “Buffalo Soldiers”. This gun has had the metal cleaned, but all markings remain. Very good cylinder scene. Back strap reads “N.M Nolan U.S.A” Nicholas Merritt Nolan was born in Ireland and immigrated to the United States just in time for the Civil War. He was originally in the 2nd Dragoons, then joined the 6th Cavalry. He was wounded twice, participated in the Gettysburg campaign along with a slew of other battles and then in 1865 became a prisoner of war. He mustered out in 1866 and quickly joined back in to the 10th Cavalry the same year. The 10th Cavalry was an all black regiment with white officers which was typical at the time. He enlisted as a 1st Lieutenant and quickly was promoted to Captain. He stayed in the 10th Cavalry in countless battles and skirmishes across Texas and the southwest, In 1883, after 16 years in the 10th Cavalry, it’s thought he had a stroke and died. He is buried in San Antonio National Cemetery in San Antonio, Texas. Along with this gun comes a binder with all of the biographical information. Captain Nolan was one tough soldier! Great Civil War, Western, Indian War, and Texas historical piece!http://www.collectorsfirearms.com/colt-10th-cavalry-identified-1860-1st-model-richards-conversion-c13238/
